I see the Pads and Phones as complimentary devices. And mostly for pleasure, not work.

Message.Title: Goldman Sachs Maintains a 'Sell' on Dell $11
Message.Msg: http://www.streetinsider.com/Analyst+Comments/Goldman+Sachs+Maintains+a+Sell+on+Dell+%28DELL%29%3B+Hitting+The+Reset+Button/7678334.html Goldman Sachs maintains a 'Sell' on Dell (NASDAQ: DELL) price target of $11.00. Analyst, Bill Shope, said, "Dell reported a revenue miss and in-line EPS for the July quarter, but its full-year outlook fell short of our already below-consensus estimate...Excluding the one-time gross margin benefit and a lower-than-expected tax rate, EPS would have been approximately in line with consensus. The company also issued disappointing guidance for 3QFY2013 and FY2013, both of which came in lower than our already below-consensus estimates." "We believe the deterioration in the stock this year and the likely sell off today, coupled with the reset of guidance to more realistic levels, suggests we are closer to a bottom. But we believe the stock could remain under pressure until the near-term risk of incremental revenue and earnings pressure eases." FY13 EPS estimate lowered from $1.78 to $1.74, FY14 from $1.84 to $1.77 and FY15 from $1.93 to $1.84.

Topic.Title: CEO is such a crook and crooks should

Message.Msg: n charges filed in U.S. District Court July 22, the SEC claimed that from 2001 to 2006, Dell violated federal securities laws and SEC rules and anti-fraud regulations in its accounting practices. In particular, according to the SEC, Dell executives failed to let investors know about large payments from Intel that had been made to convince Dell not to use processors from Advanced Micro Devices in its systems. "It was these payments rather than the company's management and operations that allowed Dell to meet its earnings targets," the SEC said in a statement July 22. "After Intel cut these payments, Dell again misled investors by not disclosing the true reason behind the company's decreased profitability." Michael Dell, former CEO Kevin Rollins and other Dell executives were charged for their roles in the disclosure violations, the SEC said. Intel's business practices have been under scrutiny for years. The chip giant has been fined or sued in several countries over the past several years for allegedly using its dominance in the x86 processor market to coerce OEMs, including Dell and Hewlett-Packard, to limit their use of AMD products. Dell was the last of the top-tier systems makers to use AMD processors. The Federal Trade Commission announced July 22 that it will review a proposed settlement of a suit against Intel over the next two weeks. Intel also is being sued by the New York Attorney General's Office and graphics chip maker Nvidia. The N.Y. Attorney General's Office has focused much of its attention on the relationship between Intel and Dell. Intel was fined $1.45 billion in 2009
